From Dave Medin Subject Re Where do U look In article writes I might add that collecting last year's data books or even ones two years out of date is usually pretty cheap and has benefits besides You usually DON'T want to base a design on a brand new There may be bugs availability may be limited the data sheets may be missing critical information that will show up in the ap notes in next year's data Kinda like buying Version of a major new software package Sometimes you get lucky but don't count on There are two more reasons to save old databooks and then beyond two years obsoleted parts and better application notes and When a part is dropped from future production planning such as the National MM series white noise generators camera sync generators it will disappear from current databooks although it still may be produced for a short time or be available from stock somewhere Now if you have some old plans calling for such a device or you have a dead gadget on your workbench and it has such a part in it you'll know the functions so you can troubleshoot and substitute as The old GE thyristor data books contain real good tutorials on SCR and triac applications that are not found elsewhere for In summary READ READ That's how you'll know what to design in which parts to use and how to solve the intractable problem that your boss has presented you It helps to have a prodigous memory for Here here Dave Medin Phone w SSD Networking h Intergraph M S Internet Huntsville AL UUCP ingr catbyte dtmedin Everywhere You Look at least around my office The opinions expressed here are mine or those of my machine